      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Gateway page, Bridge page, Jump page</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>doorway page</strong> is a thin, keyword-targeted web page created to rank for a specific search query and funnel visitors to another page. It offers no independent value to users. Google explicitly bans doorway pages under its spam policies and has run algorithm updates targeting them since <strong>March 2015</strong>.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Status</div>
            <div class="tms-value"><span class="http-code-chip err">Google spam</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">First targeted</div>
            <div class="tms-value">March 2015</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Doorway pages are the classic SEO shortcut that never worked and now actively hurts. Google's 2015 doorway update, followed by the helpful-content system, has turned them from ineffective into dangerous. If you inherited a site with dozens of location or product-variation pages, this is the term you need to understand.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a doorway page?</h2>
        <p>A doorway page is a page built to catch search traffic for a specific keyword, then push the visitor to a different page where the actual conversion happens. It is not designed to be read. It is designed to be indexed and clicked. The content is usually thin, keyword-stuffed, and near-duplicated across dozens or hundreds of similar URLs.</p>
        <p>The pattern is easy to spot: many URLs, minor keyword variations, near-identical text, aggressive redirects or single-CTA layouts, and no path back to the rest of the site.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance</div>
          <p>Google's Search Essentials list doorway pages as a spam policy violation. Google issued a specific doorway-page algorithm update in March 2015 and has reinforced enforcement through the helpful-content system. Penalties range from algorithmic demotions to site-wide manual actions labelled <em>Thin content with little or no added value</em>.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Doorway Page matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Algorithmic demotion.</strong> The March 2015 doorway update and subsequent updates deprioritise pages that match the doorway pattern.</li>
          <li><strong>Manual actions.</strong> Sites with egregious doorway networks receive Search Console penalties that can crush organic traffic overnight.</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate content.</strong> Doorway networks create hundreds of near-identical URLs that dilute link equity and waste crawl budget.</li>
          <li><strong>Trust erosion.</strong> Users who click a doorway result feel bait-and-switched and never return.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Doorway Page works</h2>
        <p>Doorway pages function as search-traffic interceptors. They target a specific query, achieve a ranking, then funnel visitors elsewhere. The doorway itself provides no genuine utility.</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># User searches for "plumber austin tx"</span><br>
          GET <span class="uf-old">/plumber-austin-tx/</span> HTTP/1.1<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Server returns thin, keyword-stuffed page + JS redirect</span><br>
          HTTP/1.1 <span class="uf-status">200 OK</span><br>
          &lt;meta http-equiv="refresh" content="0; url=/contact/"&gt;<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># User lands on generic contact form, not a plumber page</span>
        </div>
        <p>The user's search intent — "find a plumber in Austin" — is broken by the redirect. Google's algorithms detect this pattern by comparing intent, content overlap, and post-click behaviour.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Doorway Page: types and variants</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Impact</th><th>Use case</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Location spam</strong></td><td>50+ pages, city-name only difference</td><td>High penalty risk</td><td>Never — build one strong location page instead</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Affiliate funnels</strong></td><td>Thin pages redirecting to affiliate links</td><td>High penalty risk</td><td>Never</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product variations</strong></td><td>One page per SKU with no unique copy</td><td>Medium risk</td><td>Use canonical tags and expand differentiators</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Auto-generated templates</strong></td><td>Thousands of pages from a database</td><td>High risk</td><td>Consolidate or add unique value per page</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Legitimate landing pages</strong></td><td>Genuinely valuable, keyword-focused</td><td>Zero risk</td><td>Encouraged when built with substance</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Doorway Page examples</h2>
        <p>Three real doorway patterns show what to avoid and how Google treats each.</p>

        <h3>1. Location-spam network</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Plumbing company, 50+ near-identical URLs</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/plumber-austin/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/plumber-austin-tx/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/austin-plumber/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/plumbing-service-austin/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># All redirect to /contact/</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. Affiliate funnel pattern</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-old">/best-blue-widgets/</span><span class="uf-arrow">→</span><span class="uf-new">affiliate.com/blue?ref=xyz</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/best-red-widgets/</span><span class="uf-arrow">→</span><span class="uf-new">affiliate.com/red?ref=xyz</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># No unique review content, just redirects</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Template-generated e-commerce pages</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Thousands of URLs from a product database</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/product-blue-small/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/product-blue-medium/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/product-blue-large/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Only the size word differs — classic doorway signal</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Doorway page vs landing page — the difference</h2>
        <p>Both target specific keywords. Only one is allowed. The difference is whether the page provides independent value or exists purely to intercept traffic.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Landing page (allowed)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Substantial, unique content that answers the query</li>
              <li>Clear match between search intent and page content</li>
              <li>Visible in main site navigation</li>
              <li>Offers a satisfying, expected experience</li>
              <li>Google view: acceptable and encouraged</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Doorway page (banned)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Thin, near-duplicated content across URLs</li>
              <li>Redirect or funnel to another page immediately</li>
              <li>Isolated from main navigation</li>
              <li>Frustrating bait-and-switch experience</li>
              <li>Google view: spam policy violation</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for Doorway Page</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Consolidate thin pages.</strong> Merge multiple near-identical URLs into one comprehensive resource with 301 redirects.</li>
          <li><strong>Add unique value per page.</strong> For location pages: team photos, local details, testimonials. For product pages: distinct descriptions, use cases, comparisons.</li>
          <li><strong>Ensure standalone utility.</strong> Every page should be worth landing on directly, not just as a redirect stepping stone.</li>
          <li><strong>Link doorway candidates from navigation.</strong> Isolation is a doorway signal. If a page cannot be reached from a menu, ask why it exists.</li>
          <li><strong>Use canonical tags on variations.</strong> Product SKUs that share content should canonicalise to a master page.</li>
          <li><strong>Delete and 410 the truly useless.</strong> If a page has no legitimate purpose, remove it and return 410 Gone.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit quarterly.</strong> Doorway patterns creep in through CMS defaults; catch them before Google does.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — creating one location page per city</div>
          <p>Building 200 city pages by search-and-replacing the city name is the textbook doorway pattern. Either invest in genuinely unique content per city (photos, staff, service specifics, local reviews) or consolidate to a single well-built location page with a city selector. Google treats the copy-paste version as spam.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Doorway Page mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Templated location pages.</strong> Same content, city name swapped — the fastest way to trigger the doorway signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Affiliate landing pages that only redirect.</strong> Google's 2015 update was built partly to catch this pattern.</li>
          <li><strong>Product-variation pages with no differentiator.</strong> Colour/size variants should share a page or canonicalise upward.</li>
          <li><strong>Isolating doorway candidates from navigation.</strong> If a page is unreachable from the menu, it is suspicious by definition.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming small sites are safe.</strong> The doorway algorithm applies to 5-page sites and 50,000-page sites alike.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is a landing page the same as a doorway page?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. A landing page delivers substantial value to visitors and matches search intent. A doorway page offers minimal independent utility and exists solely to funnel traffic elsewhere. Google treats them very differently.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I create multiple pages targeting similar keywords?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes — but each page must offer genuinely unique, valuable content. Multiple thin pages targeting slight keyword variations is what Google penalises. Depth and differentiation are the tests.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How does Google detect doorway pages?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Through algorithmic analysis of content uniqueness, user-experience signals, keyword-targeting patterns, redirect behaviours, and post-click engagement. The 2015 doorway update and subsequent core updates all refined this detection.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the penalty for doorway pages?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Algorithmic demotions reducing rankings for affected pages, potential manual actions labelled 'Thin content with little or no added value', and in severe cases site-wide ranking impact.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How long does recovery take after fixing doorway pages?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Typically 2-4 weeks following consolidation, 301 redirects to authoritative content, and a reconsideration request in Search Console. Deeper algorithmic effects can take a full core-update cycle to unwind.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

